  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Integrated human-rural development with indigenous communities in the isolated Guatemala Highlands</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Archdiocese of Los Altos, covering the departments of Quetzaltenango and Totonicap&#xE1;n, is situated in the western highlands of Guatemala and populated mainly by Mayan communities from the K&#x2019;iche and Mam groups. Levels of poverty in the area are the second highest in the country, with 97% of the population living under the poverty line. The area is primarily rural with just 7% of the population living in urbanised settings. In Totonicap&#xE1;n municipality,  40 % of children are malnourished. . GNP per capita is  US$900 and illiteracy levels are amongst the highest in the country at 67% of the population. People suffer from lack of access to basic health and education services and adequate access to food and housing. Within the indigenous population, about 65% are Catholic, but in a form which includes many elements of Mayan spirituality. In addition, a sector of the population practices Mayan religion, while at the same time participating in the Catholic Church within a context of dialogue, reflection and shared learning.  The parish of Santa Maria Chiquimula has worked to recover and disseminate knowledge of Mayan spirituality, traditions and values as a means towards building a more integrated and inclusive church. Its integrated programme covers 37 communities of the parish, strengthening levels of community organisation and participation, providing increased opportunities for education, employment and income-generation through farming practices and improving the quality of preventive and primary health care.</narrative>
  </description>
